When attempting to create a review from a ClearCase changeset (with ClearCase running under Windows), an error message is displayed saying that 'Unable to load changeset for <changeset name>'.

Upon further inspection, it appears that the change set id that is being queried upon is incorrect.  The url generated is:

{code}
http://localhost:6060/foo/cru/create?csid=activity:some_activity@\vob&repo=Repository
{code}

However, the change set id that is being used to query the change set is *activity:some_activity@vob&repo=Repository*.  That is, the backslash included is being dropped somewhere

The ClearCase repository scanner in FishEye should only try to index changes that it hasn't already indexed. This is achieved (for base ClearCase) by issuing the command

{{cleartool lshistory -since <date>}}

We are currently using only the date, while we should be also using the time to further limit the changeset that is being indexed. The consequence is that indexing activity (and CPU usage) steadily increases during the day, drops off at midnight and then increases again.

Instead we should be using:

{{cleartool lshistory -since <date>.<time>}}

In ClearCase, users (admins really) can define custom element types. However, FishEye only considers the following element types as text files:

* {{text_file}}
* {{xml}}

The fix would be to get details about (custom) file types by executing:

{noformat}
cleartool lstype -l -kind -eltype -invob <vob>
{noformat}

any types that have a supertype (or supertype of a supertype) that equals {{text_file}} or {{xml}} should be treated as text files.

A workaround is to use only the built-in types {{text_file}} and {{xml}}.

The ClearCase support in FE tries to detect whether it is indexing a dynamic or a snapshot view. To do this, it uses the command:
{code}
ct pwv -setview -short
{code}

This command returns the view that has been set using ct setview. 

Instead, we should use
{code}
ct lsview -properties -full -cview
{code}

and parse the Properties line. This line contains 'snapshot' or 'dynamic'
